    "id": "cholesterol-lowering-2wk",
    "name": "High-Cholesterol Diet Plan — 2 Rotating Weeks (2 people)",
    "description": "Two rotating weekly menus (Monday–Sunday) designed to help lower cholesterol through diet. Weekdays include five meals (breakfast, lunch, snack, dinner, snack); weekends are lighter — breakfast and two snacks only, with no lunch or dinner. Portioned for two people who eat the same dishes: Him (~2000 kcal / 150 g protein) and Her (1600 kcal / 130 g protein).",
    "people": [
      {
        "id": "him",
        "label": "Him",
        "caloriesPerDay": { "min": 1900, "max": 2100 },
        "proteinTargetGramsPerDay": 150
      },
      {
        "id": "her",
        "label": "Her",
        "caloriesPerDay": { "min": 1550, "max": 1650 },
        "proteinTargetGramsPerDay": 130
      }
    ],
    "dietaryProfile": {
      "constraints": {
        "noAddedSugar": true,
        "maxSaturatedFatGramsPerDay": 10,
        "excludedFoods": ["red meat", "fish", "seafood"]
      }
    },
    "notes": [
      "This plan feeds two people who eat the same meals. Her portions are sized independently (not a flat scale-down of His) to hit 1600 kcal with 130 g protein: protein sources are kept high while carbs and fats are trimmed.",
      "Honey was removed from the original plan: it is classified as an added sugar (AHA) and high added-sugar intake is linked to lower HDL and higher triglycerides. Yogurt is sweetened with fruit and cinnamon instead.",
      "Use 99% lean ground turkey breast; standard 85/15 ground turkey would exceed the saturated-fat cap.",
      "Choose whole wheat/sprouted bread with no added sugar; avoid bottled stir-fry, teriyaki, and honey-mustard sauces (hidden added sugar).",
      "Raw-to-cooked ratios used: poultry cooked ≈ raw x 0.72; rice/quinoa/oats cooked ≈ dry x 3–3.5; sweet potato roasted ≈ raw x 0.80; tofu pressed & seared ≈ raw x 0.85; frozen veg and canned beans change negligibly.",
      "Macro values are estimates; actual values vary by brand and preparation.",
      "Daily totals shown are for a full weekday (all five meals). Weekends omit lunch and dinner, so weekend intake is lower — breakfast and two snacks only."
    ],
